{"title_page": "Willa Brown", "text_new": "{{short description|Aviator, educator}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = Willa Brown\n|image       = \"Willa Beatrice Brown, a 31-year-old Negro American, serves her country by training pilots for the U.S. Army Air Forces. - NARA - 535717.jpg\n|alt         =\n|caption     = Brown as a lieutenant in the [[United States Civil Air Patrol]]\n|birth_date  = {{birth date|mf=yes|1906|01|22}}\n|birth_place = [[Glasgow, Kentucky]]\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|mf=yes|1992|07|18|1906|01|22}}\n|death_place = [[Chicago, Illinois]]\n|nationality = [[United States|American]]\n|other_names =\n|known_for   = [[Civil rights]] leader<br/>First female African American pilot licensed in the United States<br/>First African American officer in the United States Civil Air Patrol<br/>First African American woman to run for [[United States Congress]]\n|occupation  = [[Pilot (aeronautics)|Pilot]], [[Lobbyist]], [[Activist]], [[Teacher]]\n|spouse   = {{Marriage|Wilbur Hardaway|November 24, 1929|1931|div}}<br>{{Marriage|[[Cornelius Coffey]]|1939|end=div}}{{efn|Most sources give the date of their marriage as 1939, but <ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\"/> gives the date as 1947 and indicates that there is no record of them marrying in 1939.}}<br>{{Marriage|Rev. J. H. Chappell|1955}}\n}}\n'''Willa Beatrice Brown''' (January 22, 1906 \u2013 July 18, 1992) was an American [[Pilot (aeronautics)|aviator]], [[lobbyist]], [[teacher]], and [[Civil Rights Movement|civil rights]] activist.<ref name=\"anb\">{{cite web |last1=Gubert |first1=Betty Kaplan |title=Brown, Willa (1906-1992), pilot and aviation educator |url=http://www.anb.org/articles/20/20-01864.html |website=American National Biography |publisher=Oxford University Press |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en| url-access=subscription}}</ref> She was the first [[African American]] woman to earn a pilot's license in the United States,<ref name=\"blackpast\">{{Cite web|title = Brown, Willa B. (1906\u20131992) |url = http://www.blackpast.org/aah/brown-willa-b-1906-1992|website = The Black Past|author=Davis, Edmond|access-date = 2016-02-09}}</ref> the first African American woman to run for the [[United States Congress]], first African American officer in the [[Civil Air Patrol]], and first woman in the U.S. to have both a pilot's license and a mechanic's license.<ref name=\":0\" /> She was a lifelong advocate for gender and racial equality in the field of aviation as well as in the military. She not only lobbied the U.S. government to integrate the [[United States Army Air Corps]] and include African Americans in the Civilian Pilot Training Program (CPTP), but also co-founded the [[Coffey School of Aeronautics]] with [[Cornelius Coffey]], the first private flight training academy owned and operated by African Americans in the U.S. She trained hundreds of pilots, several of whom went on to become [[Tuskegee Airmen]],<ref>{{Cite web|title = Our History {{!}} 99s in Aviation History {{!}} Women in Aviation |first=Kelli|last=Grant|url = http://www.ninety-nines.org/women-in-aviation-article.htm|website = The Ninety-Nines, Inc.|access-date =February 9, 2016}}</ref> and her lobbying efforts played a significant role in creation of the Tuskegee Airmen.<ref name=\"kchr.ky.gov 2020\">{{cite web | title=Willa Brown Chappell | website=kchr.ky.gov | date=2020-03-31 | url=https://kchr.ky.gov/ggbk/Pages/gbk33.aspx | access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nBrown remained politically and socially active in [[Chicago]] long after the Coffey School closed in 1945. She organized flight schools for children, ran in Congressional primary elections in 1946 and 1950, was an active member of the Westside Community Church, and taught in the Chicago Public School System until 1971, when she retired at age 65.\n\n== Early life ==\nWilla Beatrice Brown was born to Reverend and Mrs. Erice B. Brown on January 22, 1906, in [[Glasgow, Kentucky]].<ref name=\"blackpast\"/> She graduated from Wiley High School in Terra Haute, Indiana, and attended [[Indiana State University|Indiana State Teachers College]] where she graduated in 1927 with a bachelor's degree. Ten years later she earned an [[M.B.A.]] from [[Northwestern University]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|title=Black Women in America: An Historical Encyclopedia|year=1994|publisher=Indiana University Press | location= Bloomington |isbn=0-253-32774-1 | pages=184\u2013185 | chapter=Brown, Willa Beatrice (1906\u20131992)|first=Elizabeth Hadley|last=Freydberg}}</ref><ref name=\"Davis 2012\">{{cite web | last=Davis | first=Edmond | title=Willa B. Brown (1906-1992) | website=BlackPast | date=2012-07-25 | url=https://www.blackpast.org/african-american-history/brown-willa-b-1906-1992/ | access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nBrown taught in [[Gary, Indiana]] at [[Emerson High School (Indiana)|Emerson High School]]'s [[Theodore Roosevelt College and Career Academy#History|Roosevelt Annex]] from 1927 to 1932.<ref name=\"Davis 2012\"/><ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\"/> She then moved to [[Chicago]], where she worked in a variety of jobs, including secretarial work, social work, and teaching.<ref name=\"notable-black-american-women\">{{cite book |last1=Smith |first1=Jessie Carney |title=Notable Black American women |publisher=Gale Research |isbn=978-0810391772 |pages=69\u201371}}</ref> In 1934, she met [[John C. Robinson]], who introduced her to the Challenger Air Pilots Association, a group of African American pilots.<ref name=\"anb\" />\n\n== Aviation career ==\n[[File:Young Willa Brown.jpg|thumb|left|Willa Brown as a young woman, standing on an airfield]]\nIn 1934, Brown began studying at Chicago's racially segregated Harlem Field with [[Cornelius Coffey]], a certified flight instructor and expert aviation mechanic. She also began classes at [[Curtiss\u2013Wright Aeronautical University]].<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\">{{cite book |last1=Gubert |first1=Betty Kaplan |last2=Sawyer |first2=Miriam |last3=Fannin |first3=Caroline |title=Distinguished African Americans in aviation and space science |publisher=Oryx Press |isbn=978-1573562461 |pages=49\u201352|location=Westport, Conn.|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/distinguishedafr00gube}}</ref> She earned a private pilot's license in 1938<ref>{{cite news |title=YOUNG WOMAN FLYER GETS PILOT'S LICENSE: Willa Brown, Chicago Aviatrix, Can Carry Passengers, Give Instructions or Make Cross-Country Flights |work=The Pittsburgh Courier |date=2 July 1938 |page=11}}</ref> and a commercial pilot's license in 1939, becoming the first African American woman to earn either type of license in the United States.<ref name=\"anb\" /><ref name=\"chicago-tribune\">{{cite news |title=Chicago and the Tuskegee Airmen |work=Chicago Tribune |date=January 19, 2015 | location=Sec. 1 |page=14 |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/opinion/editorials/ct-tuskegee-airmen-chicago-world-war-ii-willa-brown-edit-0119-jm-20150119-story.html}}</ref>{{efn|Sources disagree on whether she was the first African American woman to earn any kind of pilot's license or the first to earn a private license; see <ref name=\"kchr.ky.gov 2020\" /> and.<ref name=\"chicago-tribune\" />}}\n\nWilla Brown, Cornelius Coffey and Enoch P. Waters worked together to form the National Negro Airmen Association of America, later renamed to National Airmen's Association of America which was incorporated in 1939. Their primary mission was to attract more interest in aviation, help develop a better understanding in the field of aeronautics and pursue more African American participation in both fields.<ref name=\"Lest We Forget 1939\">{{cite web | title=NATIONAL AIRMEN ASSOCIATION OF AMERICA ...before the Tuskegee Airmen :: World War II :: Tuskegee Airmen :: Lest We Forget | website=Lest We Forget | date=1939-08-16 | url=http://lestweforget.hamptonu.edu/page.cfm?uuid=9FEC42B7-EB34-45CE-CC673CA72120E420 | access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> As the organization's national secretary and president of the Chicago branch, Brown became an activist for racial equality. Later, she and Coffey married and established the Coffey School of Aeronautics at Harlem Airport in Chicago, where they trained black pilots and aviation mechanics.<ref name=\"cap-bio\">{{cite web |last1=Montague |first1=Carlos |title=Willa Brown: Pioneer for Female & African American Aviation |url=https://www.cap.news/willa-brown-pioneer-for-female--african-american-aviation/ |website=Willa Brown: Pioneer for Female & African American Aviation |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n[[File:LIEUT. WILLA BROWN - AVIATRIX-MAKER OF PILOTS - NARA - 535627.tif|thumb|Office for Emergency Management publication featuring Brown]]\nShe lobbied the government continuously, advocating for integration of black pilots into a then-segregated Army Air Corps and the federal [[Civilian Pilot Training Program]] (CPTP), the latter of which was a system established by the Civil Aeronautics Authority to provide a pool of civilian pilots for use during national emergencies. She also worked to disprove a 1925 [[United States Army War College|Army War College]] study which had deemed African Americans unfit to fly.<ref name=\"chicago-tribune\" /> She lobbied the federal government to award CPTP contracts to train African American pilots. In 1940, she was appointed coordinator of the Chicago units of the CPTP, and the Coffey School was selected by the U.S. Army to provide black trainees for the Air Corps pilot training program.<ref name=\"notable-black-american-women\" /> Nearly 200 students from the school went on to join the [[Tuskeegee Airmen]].<ref name=\"tuskegee-airmen\">{{cite web |title=Willa Beatrice Brown |url=http://tuskegeeairmen.org/wp-content/uploads/Willa-Brown-Bio.pdf |website=Tuskegee Airmen Inc. |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> In 1942, she attained the rank of Lieutenant in Civil Air Patrol Squadron 613-6, becoming the first African American officer in the Civil Air Patrol.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\"/> She eventually became the coordinator of war-training service for the Civil Aeronautics Authority.<ref>{{cite web |title=WILLA BROWN |url=http://www.hill.af.mil/library/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=5858 |website=Hill Air Force Base |accessdate=30 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160328143509/http://www.hill.af.mil/library/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=5858 |archivedate=28 Mar 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Post-aviation career ==\nIn 1946, Brown ran in the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] primary elections for [[Illinois's 1st congressional district]], becoming the first African American woman to in a Congressional primary election.<ref>{{cite news |title=WILLA B. BROWN VIEWS POLITICS AS NEW CRUSADE |work=Chicago Daily Tribune |date=31 Mar 1946 |page=S4}}</ref> She was defeated by William E. King.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wilson |first1=Edward |title=BUSBEY VICTORY OUTSTANDING IN CONGRESS RACES |work=Chicago Daily Tribune |date=11 Apr 1946 |page=2}}</ref> She ran for the same Congressional seat in the 1950 Republican primary election, and was defeated by [[Archibald Carey Jr.]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Harold |title=G. O. P. STARTS WORK TO REGAIN CONGRESS POSTS: Leaders Hail Primary Spats as Robustness |work=Chicago Daily Tribune |date=13 Apr 1950 |page=19}}</ref>\n\nBrown returned to teaching in high schools from 1962 until her retirement in 1971. She taught business and aeronautics.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\" />\n\nIn 1971, Brown was appointed to the [[Federal Aviation Administration]]'s Women's Advisory Committee, the first black woman serving on the committee. She served on the committee until 1974.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\"/>\n\n== Awards and recognition ==\nIn 1939, Brown was cited in the 76th [[Congressional Record]] for achievements in aviation.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\" />\n\nIn 2010, Brown was awarded the Distinguished Alumni Award by the [[Indiana University of Pennsylvania|Indiana State University]] Alumni Association.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McCormick |first1=Mike |title=The amazing life of Willa Beatrice Brown |url=https://www.tribstar.com/community/the-amazing-life-of-willa-beatrice-brown/article_33082107-864e-5e6c-a533-83cadb601f43.html |website=Tribune-Star |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite web\n| last1 = Freydberg\n| first1 = Elizabeth Amelia Hadley\n| title = Aviation\n| url = http://search.credoreference.com/content/entry/rcuswh/aviation/0\n| website = Credo\n| publisher = Houghton Mifflin Company\n| accessdate = 9 September 2017\n}}\n\n*{{cite book|last1=Johnson|first1=Jesse J.|title=Black women in the Armed Forces, 1942-1974 : (a pictorial history)|date=1974|publisher=Johnson|location=Hampton, Va.|isbn=9780915044115|edition=1st}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Gibson|first1=Karen Bush|title=Women aviators : 26 stories of pioneer flights, daring missions, and record-setting journeys|date=2013|publisher=Chicago Review Press|location=Chicago, Ill.|isbn=9781613745403|edition=1st|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/womenaviators26s0000gibs}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist-la}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Kentucky Women Remembered|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brown, Willa}}\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1992 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Glasgow, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:African-American educators]]\n[[Category:20th-century American educators]]\n[[Category:African-American female military personnel]]\n[[Category:American women in World War II]]\n[[Category:Indiana State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Women in the United States Army]]\n[[Category:American female aviators]]\n[[Category:Kentucky women aviators]]\n[[Category:African-American aviators]]\n[[Category:African-American female aviators]]\n[[Category:Illinois Republicans]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Aviator, educator}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = Willa Brown\n|image       = \"Willa Beatrice Brown, a 31-year-old Negro American, serves her country by training pilots for the U.S. Army Air Forces. - NARA - 535717.jpg\n|alt         =\n|caption     = Brown as a lieutenant in the [[United States Civil Air Patrol]]\n|birth_date  = {{birth date|mf=yes|1906|01|22}}\n|birth_place = [[Glasgow, Kentucky]]\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|mf=yes|1992|07|18|1906|01|22}}\n|death_place = [[Chicago, Illinois]]\n|nationality = [[United States|American]]\n|other_names =\n|known_for   = [[Civil rights]] leader<br/>First female African American pilot licensed in the United States<br/>First African American officer in the United States Civil Air Patrol<br/>First African American woman to run for [[United States Congress]]\n|occupation  = [[Pilot (aeronautics)|Pilot]], [[Lobbyist]], [[Activist]], [[Teacher]]\n|spouse   = {{Marriage|Wilbur Hardaway|November 24, 1929|1931|div}}<br>{{Marriage|[[Cornelius Coffey]]|1939|end=div}}{{efn|Most sources give the date of their marriage as 1939, but <ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\"/> gives the date as 1947 and indicates that there is no record of them marrying in 1939.}}<br>{{Marriage|Rev. J. H. Chappell|1955}}\n}}\n'''Willa Beatrice Brown''' (January 22, 1906 \u2013 July 18, 1992) was an American [[Pilot (aeronautics)|aviator]], [[lobbyist]], [[teacher]], and [[Civil Rights Movement|civil rights]] activist.<ref name=\"anb\">{{cite web |last1=Gubert |first1=Betty Kaplan |title=Brown, Willa (1906-1992), pilot and aviation educator |url=http://www.anb.org/articles/20/20-01864.html |website=American National Biography |publisher=Oxford University Press |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en| url-access=subscription}}</ref> She was the first [[African American]] woman to earn a pilot's license in the United States,<ref name=\"blackpast\">{{Cite web|title = Brown, Willa B. (1906\u20131992) |url = http://www.blackpast.org/aah/brown-willa-b-1906-1992|website = The Black Past|author=Davis, Edmond|access-date = 2016-02-09}}</ref> the first African American woman to run for the [[United States Congress]], first African American officer in the [[Civil Air Patrol]], and first woman in the U.S. to have both a pilot's license and a mechanic's license.<ref name=\":0\" /> She was a lifelong advocate for gender and racial equality in the field of aviation as well as in the military. She not only lobbied the U.S. government to integrate the [[United States Army Air Corps]] and include African Americans in the Civilian Pilot Training Program (CPTP), but also co-founded the [[Coffey School of Aeronautics]] with [[Cornelius Coffey]], the first private flight training academy owned and operated by African Americans in the U.S. She trained hundreds of pilots, several of whom went on to become [[Tuskegee Airmen]],<ref>{{Cite web|title = Our History {{!}} 99s in Aviation History {{!}} Women in Aviation |first=Kelli|last=Grant|url = http://www.ninety-nines.org/women-in-aviation-article.htm|website = The Ninety-Nines, Inc.|access-date =February 9, 2016}}</ref> and her lobbying efforts played a significant role in creation of the Tuskegee Airmen.<ref name=\"kchr.ky.gov 2020\">{{cite web | title=Willa Brown Chappell | website=kchr.ky.gov | date=2020-03-31 | url=https://kchr.ky.gov/ggbk/Pages/gbk33.aspx | access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nBrown remained politically and socially active in [[Chicago]] long after the Coffey School closed in 1945. She organized flight schools for children, ran in Congressional primary elections in 1946 and 1950, was an active member of the Westside Community Church, and taught in the Chicago Public School System until 1971, when she retired at age 65.\n\n== Early life ==\nWilla Beatrice Brown was born to Reverend and Mrs. Erice B. Brown on January 22, 1906, in [[Glasgow, Kentucky]].<ref name=\"blackpast\"/> She graduated from Wiley High School in Terra Haute, Indiana, and attended [[Indiana State University|Indiana State Teachers College]] where she graduated in 1927 with a bachelor's degree. Ten years later she earned an [[M.B.A.]] from [[Northwestern University]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|title=Black Women in America: An Historical Encyclopedia|year=1994|publisher=Indiana University Press | location= Bloomington |isbn=0-253-32774-1 | pages=184\u2013185 | chapter=Brown, Willa Beatrice (1906\u20131992)|first=Elizabeth Hadley|last=Freydberg}}</ref><ref name=\"Davis 2012\">{{cite web | last=Davis | first=Edmond | title=Willa B. Brown (1906-1992) | website=BlackPast | date=2012-07-25 | url=https://www.blackpast.org/african-american-history/brown-willa-b-1906-1992/ | access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nBrown taught in [[Gary, Indiana]] at [[Emerson High School (Indiana)|Emerson High School]]'s [[Theodore Roosevelt College and Career Academy#History|Roosevelt Annex]] from 1927 to 1932.<ref name=\"Davis 2012\"/><ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\"/> She then moved to [[Chicago]], where she worked in a variety of jobs, including secretarial work, social work, and teaching.<ref name=\"notable-black-american-women\">{{cite book |last1=Smith |first1=Jessie Carney |title=Notable Black American women |publisher=Gale Research |isbn=978-0810391772 |pages=69-71}}</ref> In 1934, she met [[John C. Robinson]], who introduced her to the Challenger Air Pilots Association, a group of African American pilots.<ref name=\"anb\" />\n\n== Aviation career ==\n[[File:Young Willa Brown.jpg|thumb|left|Willa Brown as a young woman, standing on an airfield]]\nIn 1934, Brown began studying at Chicago's racially segregated Harlem Field with [[Cornelius Coffey]], a certified flight instructor and expert aviation mechanic. She also began classes at [[Curtiss\u2013Wright Aeronautical University]].<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\">{{cite book |last1=Gubert |first1=Betty Kaplan |last2=Sawyer |first2=Miriam |last3=Fannin |first3=Caroline |title=Distinguished African Americans in aviation and space science |publisher=Oryx Press |isbn=978-1573562461 |pages=49-52|location=Westport, Conn.|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/distinguishedafr00gube}}</ref> She earned a private pilot's license in 1938<ref>{{cite news |title=YOUNG WOMAN FLYER GETS PILOT'S LICENSE: Willa Brown, Chicago Aviatrix, Can Carry Passengers, Give Instructions or Make Cross-Country Flights |work=The Pittsburgh Courier |date=2 July 1938 |page=11}}</ref> and a commercial pilot's license in 1939, becoming the first African American woman to earn either type of license in the United States.<ref name=\"anb\" /><ref name=\"chicago-tribune\">{{cite news |title=Chicago and the Tuskegee Airmen |work=Chicago Tribune |date=January 19, 2015 | location=Sec. 1 |page=14 |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/opinion/editorials/ct-tuskegee-airmen-chicago-world-war-ii-willa-brown-edit-0119-jm-20150119-story.html}}</ref>{{efn|Sources disagree on whether she was the first African American woman to earn any kind of pilot's license or the first to earn a private license; see <ref name=\"kchr.ky.gov 2020\" /> and <ref name=\"chicago-tribune\" />.}} \n\nWilla Brown, Cornelius Coffey and Enoch P. Waters worked together to form the National Negro Airmen Association of America, later renamed to National Airmen's Association of America which was incorporated in 1939. Their primary mission was to attract more interest in aviation, help develop a better understanding in the field of aeronautics and pursue more African American participation in both fields.<ref name=\"Lest We Forget 1939\">{{cite web | title=NATIONAL AIRMEN ASSOCIATION OF AMERICA ...before the Tuskegee Airmen :: World War II :: Tuskegee Airmen :: Lest We Forget | website=Lest We Forget | date=1939-08-16 | url=http://lestweforget.hamptonu.edu/page.cfm?uuid=9FEC42B7-EB34-45CE-CC673CA72120E420 | access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> As the organization's national secretary and president of the Chicago branch, Brown became an activist for racial equality. Later, she and Coffey married and established the Coffey School of Aeronautics at Harlem Airport in Chicago, where they trained black pilots and aviation mechanics.<ref name=\"cap-bio\">{{cite web |last1=Montague |first1=Carlos |title=Willa Brown: Pioneer for Female & African American Aviation |url=https://www.cap.news/willa-brown-pioneer-for-female--african-american-aviation/ |website=Willa Brown: Pioneer for Female & African American Aviation |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n[[File:LIEUT. WILLA BROWN - AVIATRIX-MAKER OF PILOTS - NARA - 535627.tif|thumb|Office for Emergency Management publication featuring Brown]]\nShe lobbied the government continuously, advocating for integration of black pilots into a then-segregated Army Air Corps and the federal [[Civilian Pilot Training Program]] (CPTP), the latter of which was a system established by the Civil Aeronautics Authority to provide a pool of civilian pilots for use during national emergencies. She also worked to disprove a 1925 [[United States Army War College|Army War College]] study which had deemed African Americans unfit to fly.<ref name=\"chicago-tribune\" /> She lobbied the federal government to award CPTP contracts to train African American pilots. In 1940, she was appointed coordinator of the Chicago units of the CPTP, and the Coffey School was selected by the U.S. Army to provide black trainees for the Air Corps pilot training program.<ref name=\"notable-black-american-women\" /> Nearly 200 students from the school went on to join the [[Tuskeegee Airmen]].<ref name=\"tuskegee-airmen\">{{cite web |title=Willa Beatrice Brown |url=http://tuskegeeairmen.org/wp-content/uploads/Willa-Brown-Bio.pdf |website=Tuskegee Airmen Inc. |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> In 1942, she attained the rank of Lieutenant in Civil Air Patrol Squadron 613-6, becoming the first African American officer in the Civil Air Patrol.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\"/> She eventually became the coordinator of war-training service for the Civil Aeronautics Authority.<ref>{{cite web |title=WILLA BROWN |url=http://www.hill.af.mil/library/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=5858 |website=Hill Air Force Base |accessdate=30 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160328143509/http://www.hill.af.mil/library/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=5858 |archivedate=28 Mar 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Post-aviation career ==\nIn 1946, Brown ran in the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] primary elections for [[Illinois's 1st congressional district]], becoming the first African American woman to in a Congressional primary election.<ref>{{cite news |title=WILLA B. BROWN VIEWS POLITICS AS NEW CRUSADE |work=Chicago Daily Tribune |date=31 Mar 1946 |page=S4}}</ref> She was defeated by William E. King.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wilson |first1=Edward |title=BUSBEY VICTORY OUTSTANDING IN CONGRESS RACES |work=Chicago Daily Tribune |date=11 Apr 1946 |page=2}}</ref> She ran for the same Congressional seat in the 1950 Republican primary election, and was defeated by [[Archibald Carey Jr.]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Harold |title=G. O. P. STARTS WORK TO REGAIN CONGRESS POSTS: Leaders Hail Primary Spats as Robustness |work=Chicago Daily Tribune |date=13 Apr 1950 |page=19}}</ref>\n\nBrown returned to teaching in high schools from 1962 until her retirement in 1971. She taught business and aeronautics.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\" />\n\nIn 1971, Brown was appointed to the [[Federal Aviation Administration]]'s Women's Advisory Committee, the first black woman serving on the committee. She served on the committee until 1974.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans />\n\n== Awards and recognition ==\nIn 1939, Brown was cited in the 76th [[Congressional Record]] for achievements in aviation.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\" />\n\nIn 2010, Brown was awarded the Distinguished Alumni Award by the [[Indiana University of Pennsylvania|Indiana State University]] Alumni Association.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McCormick |first1=Mike |title=The amazing life of Willa Beatrice Brown |url=https://www.tribstar.com/community/the-amazing-life-of-willa-beatrice-brown/article_33082107-864e-5e6c-a533-83cadb601f43.html |website=Tribune-Star |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Further Reading ==\n*{{cite web\n| last1 = Freydberg\n| first1 = Elizabeth Amelia Hadley\n| title = Aviation\n| url = http://search.credoreference.com/content/entry/rcuswh/aviation/0\n| website = Credo\n| publisher = Houghton Mifflin Company\n| accessdate = 9 September 2017\n}}\n\n*{{cite book|last1=Johnson|first1=Jesse J.|title=Black women in the Armed Forces, 1942-1974 : (a pictorial history)|date=1974|publisher=Johnson|location=Hampton, Va.|isbn=9780915044115|edition=1st}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Gibson|first1=Karen Bush|title=Women aviators : 26 stories of pioneer flights, daring missions, and record-setting journeys|date=2013|publisher=Chicago Review Press|location=Chicago, Ill.|isbn=9781613745403|edition=1st|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/womenaviators26s0000gibs}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist-la}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Kentucky Women Remembered|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brown, Willa}}\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1992 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Glasgow, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:African-American educators]]\n[[Category:20th-century American educators]]\n[[Category:African-American female military personnel]]\n[[Category:American women in World War II]]\n[[Category:Indiana State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Women in the United States Army]]\n[[Category:American female aviators]]\n[[Category:Kentucky women aviators]]\n[[Category:African-American aviators]]\n[[Category:African-American female aviators]]\n[[Category:Illinois Republicans]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "ref name", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Willa_Brown"}
{"title_page": "Wojciech \u0141ukaszewski", "text_new": "{{Expand Polish|topic=culture|date=January 2012|Wojciech \u0141ukaszewski}}\n'''Wojciech \u0141ukaszewski''', born 10 March 1936 in [[Cz\u0119stochowa]] \u2013 13 April 1978 in [[Cz\u0119stochowa]], was a [[Poland|Polish]] [[composer]], [[pedagogue]], [[Songwriter|music writer]] and musical impresario. His father, Antoni \u0141ukaszewski, worked in a legal firm and was a participant in the [[Silesian Uprising|Third Silesian Uprising]]. His mother's name was Helena, n\u00e9e Michalska. In 1963, he married Maria Patrzyk, and they had two sons, the composer [[Pawe\u0142 \u0141ukaszewski]] and the musician and author [[Marcin \u0141ukaszewski (musician)|Marcin \u0141ukaszewski]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Lukaszewski|title=Wojciech \u0141ukaszewski - 1936-1978|url=http://www.lukaszewski.waw.pl/|work=Biografia|publisher=Lukaszewski.waw.pl|accessdate=18 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Literature==\n*Marcin Lukaszewski (1997), ''Wojciech Lukaszewski \u2013 \u017cycie i tw\u00f3rczo\u015b\u0107'', WSP Publishing, [[Czestochowa]]. {{ISBN|83-7098-254-9}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lukaszewski, Wojciech}}\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:1978 deaths]]\n[[Category:Polish composers]]\n[[Category:People from Cz\u0119stochowa]]\n[[Category:Writers about music]]\n[[Category:20th-century composers]]\n\n\n{{Poland-composer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Expand Polish|topic=culture|date=January 2012|Wojciech \u0141ukaszewski}}\n'''Wojciech \u0141ukaszewski''', born 10 March 1936 in [[Cz\u0119stochowa]] \u2013 13 April 1978 in [[Cz\u0119stochowa]], was a [[Poland|Polish]] [[composer]], [[pedagogue]], [[Songwriter|music writer]] and musical impresario. His father, Antoni \u0141ukaszewski, worked in a legal firm and was a participant in the [[Silesian Uprising|Third Silesian Uprising]].His mother's name was Helena, n\u00e9e Michalska. In 1963, he married Maria Patrzyk, and they had two sons, the composer [[Pawe\u0142 \u0141ukaszewski]] and the musician and author [[Marcin \u0141ukaszewski (musician)|Marcin \u0141ukaszewski]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Lukaszewski|title=Wojciech \u0141ukaszewski - 1936-1978|url=http://www.lukaszewski.waw.pl/|work=Biografia|publisher=Lukaszewski.waw.pl|accessdate=18 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Literature==\n*Marcin Lukaszewski (1997), ''Wojciech Lukaszewski \u2013 \u017cycie i tw\u00f3rczo\u015b\u0107'', WSP Publishing, [[Czestochowa]]. {{ISBN|83-7098-254-9}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lukaszewski, Wojciech}}\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:1978 deaths]]\n[[Category:Polish composers]]\n[[Category:People from Cz\u0119stochowa]]\n[[Category:Writers about music]]\n[[Category:20th-century composers]]\n\n\n{{Poland-composer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Benedyktyn1", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wojciech_%C5%81ukaszewski"}
{"title_page": "Aldridge", "text_new": "{{for|other uses of the term Aldridge|Aldridge (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country = England\n|map_type= West Midlands\n|coordinates = {{coord|52.606|-1.91787|display=inline,title}}\n|static_image_name= St Mary's Church, Aldridge - 03.JPG\n|static_image_caption= St Mary's Church, Aldridge\n|population = 39,348\n|population_ref = ([[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census.Ward]])<ref name=\"key\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/reports/localarea?compare=E05001308|title=Brownhills Ward (as of 2011)|publisher=Office for National Statistics|accessdate=26 June 2019}}</ref>\n|official_name= Aldridge\n|metropolitan_borough= [[Metropolitan Borough of Walsall|Walsall]]\n|region= West Midlands\n|metropolitan_county= [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]]\n|constituency_westminster= [[Aldridge-Brownhills (UK Parliament constituency)|Aldridge-Brownhills]]\n|london_distance= {{convert|128|mi|km|abbr=on}} [[Boxing the compass|SE]]\n|post_town= WALSALL\n|postcode_district = WS9\n|postcode_area= WS\n|dial_code= 01543, 01922\n|os_grid_reference= SK056009\n}}\n\n[[File:Gold postbox on the High Street - geograph.org.uk - 3132414.jpg|thumb|Gold postbox on the High Street]]\n\n'''Aldridge''' is a town and civil parish in the [[Walsall Metropolitan Borough|Walsall Borough]], [[West Midlands (region)|West Midlands]], [[England]]. [[Historic counties of England|Historically]] a village that was part of [[Staffordshire]] until 1974.\n\nIt is {{convert|3|mi}} from [[Brownhills]], {{convert|5|mi|0}} north east of [[Walsall]], {{convert|6|mi}} from [[Sutton Coldfield]] and {{convert|7|mi}} from [[Lichfield]]. Aldridge has a mixture of social and private housing, there is a large 1960s built shopping centre which has fairly high occupation rates, and a large number of industrial estates supporting both heavy and light industries.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Aldridge war memorial - 02.JPG|thumb|Aldridge war memorial]]\n\nAldridge was recorded as a settlement in the [[Domesday Book]] of 1086, though the now much larger settlement of Walsall was not.<ref>[http://www.haughton.net/domesdaybookplaces_a.htm THE DOMESDAY BOOK INDEX 1086 - 'A' Places ( Domesday Book Settlements / Places )<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928030248/http://www.haughton.net/domesdaybookplaces_a.htm |date=28 September 2007 }}</ref> It was valued at 15 shillings under the name of \"Alrewic\", which may have originated from an abundance of Alder trees in the area.<ref>[http://www.walsall.gov.uk/aldridge_in_history.htm Aldridge in history<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Another suggestion is that the name \"Aldbridge\" means \"outlying farm among alder-trees\", from the [[Old English]] ''alor'' and ''w\u012bc''.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Place-names of Great Britain and Ireland|last=Field|first=John|date=1980|publisher=David & Charles|isbn=0389201545|location=Newton Abbot, Devon|oclc=6964610|page=23}}</ref>\n\nAldridge began as a small agricultural settlement, with farming being the most common occupation up until the 19th century.\n\nIn the 1800s, Aldridge became an industrial town with [[coal mine]]s and [[lime kiln]]s. The coal and clay in the area prompted many to set up collieries and brickworks. Aldridge clay is especially useful in the manufacture of blue bricks. The 1881 census shows that the mines and brickworks were major employers. Because the coal and clay beneath the eastern side of Aldridge (towards Stonnall) is located much deeper under the surface, extraction of this coal and clay would not have been economically viable. As a result, farms continued to dominate the eastern part, though a sand quarry was set up and still remains on Birch Lane.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070621175821/http://www.btinternet.com/~aldridgelhs/HISTORY.htm A Brief History<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nDuring the 20th century, modern shops were built in the centre of Aldridge, as well as council buildings. After the [[Second World War]] Aldridge became a [[dormitory town]], or [[suburb]], of [[Birmingham]]. A small airport called Aldridge Airport was used during the Second World War and after was used for passenger services.\n\nAldridge became an [[Urban district (Great Britain and Ireland)|urban district]] in [[Staffordshire]] in 1894. Other [[village]]s within the district included [[Pelsall]], [[Walsall Wood]], [[Clayhanger, Walsall|Clayhanger]] and [[Streetly]]. This merged with [[Brownhills]] in 1966 to form [[Aldridge-Brownhills Urban District|Aldridge-Brownhills]], and then became part of the Metropolitan Borough of Walsall in 1974.\n\n==Demography==\nThe recorded population in 2011 in 26,988.<ref>[http://www.statistics.gov.uk/census2001/west_midlands_urban_area.asp National Statistics Online - Census 2001<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n== Politics ==\nSince 1979, Aldridge's [[Member of Parliament|MP]] was [[Richard Shepherd]] ([[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]), the MP for [[Aldridge-Brownhills (UK Parliament constituency)|Aldridge-Brownhills]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.election.demon.co.uk/1997EB.html |title=British Parliamentary Election results 1997-: English Boroughs part 1 |publisher=Election.demon.co.uk |date=1995-03-01 |accessdate=2010-05-02| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100503052817/http://www.election.demon.co.uk/1997EB.html| archivedate= 3 May 2010 <!--DASHBot-->|url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.election.demon.co.uk/1983EB.html |title=United Kingdom Parliamentary Election results 1983-97: English Boroughs part 1 |publisher=Election.demon.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2010-05-02}}</ref> He stood down at the 2015 General Election. In May 2015 [[Wendy Morton]] was selected as the new MP. Aldridge-Brownhills is a safe Conservative seat.\n\nAldridge is made up of two council wards: Aldridge Central & South, Aldridge North & Walsall Wood. There are three Conservative Councillors for Aldridge Central & South: John Murray, John Rochelle & Tim Wilson.\nAldridge North & Walsall Wood is also covered by three Conservative councillors: Keith Sears, Anthony Harris and Gary Clarke.<ref>[http://www.walsall.gov.uk/index/council_and_democracy/decision_making_in_walsall/councillors.htm#acs Current Walsall Councillors]</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nAldridge has a number of primary and secondary schools. The primary schools are Cooper and Jordan (CE), Leighswood, St Mary of the Angels (Catholic) and Whetstone Field (Redhouse primary school was closed in the summer of 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.walsall.gov.uk/CMISWebPublic/Binary.ashx?Document=1118 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-07-30 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723053233/http://www2.walsall.gov.uk/CMISWebPublic/Binary.ashx?Document=1118 |archivedate=2011-07-23 }}</ref>). The secondary schools are [[Aldridge School]] and [[St Francis of Assisi Catholic Technology College]].\n\n==Industry and commerce==\nIn Aldridge there are a number of factories, mostly located on Empire Industrial Park, but also towards Walsall Wood along the main road, Northgate. Some of the most notable factories include the large [[Ibstock]] brick works,  and the [[GKN Driveline|GKN Driveshafts]] factory, although the latter company closed in recent years due to relocation and cheaper foreign imports. [[Birlec]], a manufacturer of industrial furnaces relocated to Aldridge in the late 1950s, but has since closed. Aldridge Plastics Ltd, a plastics injection moulder, was set up in the town in 1968 and continued trading for almost 40 years before ceasing production in 2007. From January 2011, GFP Engineering Ltd, a Glass Reinforced Plastic (GRP) moulding company, will commence trading after relocating from nearby Lichfield.{{citation needed|reason=update evidence required|date=November 2014}} There is also a marina, Aldridge Marina, which recently underwent full refurbishment offering facilities for canal boat moorers.\n\nMost of the towns shops are located either on High Street, Anchor Road, or in the shopping area known as \"The Parade\". Well-known shops here include [[WH Smith]], [[Iceland]] supermarket, [[Home Bargains]], and [[Boots The Chemist]]. A purpose-built [[Safeway (UK)]] opened in 1992 and started operating as a [[Morrisons]] from 2004. [[B & M]] took over the former [[Focus DIY]] in Coppice Lane and opened its doors for the first time on 1 August 2015. One of the oldest traders in Aldridge is R.H.N. Riley Insurances on Anchor Rd, they have been trading since 1957 and in Aldridge since about 1970. Also in the area is the relatively newly opened Wetherspoons Public House - it has refurbished the former Avion cinema, latterly a bingo hall before the transition to pub. Many of the original features have been retained including the protected facade. There are a good deal of eateries in the town and these are regularly enjoyed by locals and travellers from further afield.\n\n== Transport ==\n\nAldridge is served by local bus services. Many of the buses in Aldridge were renumbered in April 2010 as part of National Express West Midlands' attempt to simplify bus services in and around the Walsall area. Bus operators operating services through Aldridge are\n[[Diamond West Midlands]] and [[National Express West Midlands]]. Services operated are to Walsall, Birmingham, Brownhills and Lichfield.\n\n[[File:Aldridge station, with Society Special train, 1951 (geograph 5039140).jpg|thumb|Aldridge station, with Society Special train, 1951]]\n\n[[Aldridge railway station]] was on the [[Sutton Park Line]] running from Walsall to [[Birmingham]] via Sutton Coldfield. It also had a direct link to [[Wolverhampton]] on the now defunct [[Wolverhampton and Walsall Railway]]. As well as a direct link to Brownhills via Walsall Wood although this closed in 1960s. The station had services to Walsall, Birmingham, Wolverhampton and Brownhills that operated services for passengers. The station was closed in 1966 and since then the line has been used only for freight. Ongoing speculation about returning passenger services to Aldridge, which would require a new station to be built, has continued with the apparent inclusion of Aldridge and [[Streetly]] stations on a map in the 2016 West Midlands Strategic Transport Plan.<ref>https://www.wmca.org.uk/media/1371/2016-06-01-mfg-summary-document_wmca.pdf</ref>\n\n== Sports, recreation and entertainment ==\nAldridge has a cricket and hockey club called \"The Stick and Wicket\", located on the green behind the parish church, [[St. Mary's Church, Aldridge|St. Mary's]], and the Masonic Hall. Aldridge Hockey Club merged with Walsall Hockey Club in 2011; it is now known as Aldridge & Walsall Hockey Club.<ref>http://www.awhockey.co.uk</ref>\n\nAldridge Sailing Club was formed in 1967 and celebrated its 50th anniversary in 2017. \nIt is an RYA affiliated club and offers regular training courses. It is located on Barns lane / Stubbers Green Road. www.aldridgesc.org.uk\n\nAldridge Rugby Football Club was formed in 1998 from an amalgamation of two established rugby clubs based in Birmingham: Witton and Old Centrals.\nThe club is based on the former Old Centrals sports ground at Bourne Vale in Aldridge and currently plays in Midlands 5 West (North), fielding three senior sides.\n\nAldridge Compass Suites (based at the Masonic Hall on the Green) is a venue for wedding receptions, christenings and other functions.\n\nThe Aldridge Youth Theatre, was officially opened by the actor [[Bernard Hepton]] and is located on Noddy Park Road by the Croft. It is run by a group of volunteers and puts on a variety of plays throughout the year. A pantomime is usually staged in January.\n\nAir Cadets: 425 (Aldridge) Squadron, part of Staffordshire Wing of the [[Air Training Corps]] was formed in 1941 and currently occupies a purpose-built HQ close to the village centre. The Squadron is run by uniformed [[RAFVR(T)]] officers and ATC SNCO adult staff, assisted by civilian instructors and a padre.\n\nThe 36th Walsall 1st Aldridge scout group is located on Middlemore Lane, opposite Anchor Meadow, and runs Beaver, Cub, Scout and Explorer sections for boys aged 6 and upwards. The beavers are aged 6\u20138, cubs are aged 8\u201310/11, scouts are aged 11\u201314 and explorers are aged 14\u201318.\n\nThe Methodist church, is used by 1st Aldridge Girl guides, as well as two brownie groups and a rainbow group. The rainbows group is for girls aged 5\u20137, the brownies for girls aged 7\u201310, and guides aged 10\u201314. Older girls do take part, and are known as the senior section.\n\nSt. Mary's Parish Church has one of the largest church youth groups in the area.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}} Around 90 young people, between the ages of 13 and 18, attend the group. The group also hosts an annual summer camp in Wales (in recent years attracting over 100 teenagers), as well as a weekend away in February.\n\nThe 33rd Walsall Scout group is based at Aldridge Methodist Church and holds Beavers, Cubs and scouts for boys and girls aged 6\u201314. They go on annual scout camps and have been to Beaudesert Campsite and Blackwell Adventure.\n\nThe 49th Walsall Scout Group is the third Scout Group in Aldridge based at St. Thomas's Church at the bottom of St Thomas Close, on the estate just off Lazy Hill Road and Greenwood Road, it also caters for boys and girls between the ages of 6 and 18.\n\n==Suburbs==\nSuburbs and villages of the town include: Castlefort (Part), [[Walsall Wood]] (Part), Leighswood, Druids Heath.\n\n==Notable residents==\n===Military===\n[[Air Chief Marshal]] Sir [[Stuart Peach|Stuart William Peach]], [[Order of the British Empire|GBE]], [[Order of the Bath|KCB]], [[Aide-de-camp|ADC]], [[Deputy Lieutenant|DL]] was educated at Aldridge Grammar School.<ref>[https://www.gov.uk/government/people/stuart-peach]</ref>\n\n=== Military honours ===\n[[Charles George Bonner]] VC, DSC (29 December 1884 \u2013 7 February 1951), born in Aldridge, was an English recipient of the [[Victoria Cross]], the highest and most prestigious award for gallantry in the face of the enemy that can be awarded to [[United Kingdom|British]] and [[Commonwealth#Great Britain|Commonwealth]] forces. Bonner Grove is a well-maintained neighbourhood of social housing flats and privately owned houses in Aldridge that remembers his name.\n\n=== Sports men and women ===\n[[Charles Holland (cyclist)|Charles Holland]] was a road bicycle racer, and one of the first two Britons to ride the Tour de France. Rode in Olympic Games: Los Angeles 1932 and Berlin 1936.{{Citation needed|date=February 2011}}\n\n[[Vic Milne]] had a doctor's surgery in Portland Road,  Aldridge.{{citation needed|date=March 2013}}  Played football for [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]], including an appearance in the [[1924 FA Cup Final]] where his team were defeated 2-0 by [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]].\n\n[[Lee Sinnott]] (born 12 July 1965 in Aldridge) is an English ex-professional footballer and was the manager of [[Farsley Celtic F.C.|Farsley Celtic]], whom he led to promotion three times in four years. He went on to manage [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] for a short period. He began his career at [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]] as an apprentice, and played in the 1984 [[FA Cup]] final for his next club [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] in 1984. He captained [[Huddersfield Town F.C.|Huddersfield Town]] to [[Football League Second Division|Division Two]] playoff glory in 1995.\n\n[[Colin Charvis]], former captain of the [[Wales national rugby union team]], went to the Redhouse School in Aldridge.<ref>http://www.birminghammail.net/news/top-stories/2010/05/15/former-wales-rugby-captain-colin-charvis-returned-to-his-walsall-roots-97319-26448153/</ref>\n\nSwimmer [[Ellie Simmonds]] won two gold medals at both the 2008 and 2012 [[Paralympics]]. She attended Cooper and Jordan Primary School, then [[Aldridge School]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Davies |first=Gareth A |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/paralympicsport/2964791/Eleanor-Simmonds-claims-two-gold-swimming-medals-at-the-2008-Paralympics-in-Beijing-Paralympics.html |title=Eleanor Simmonds claims two gold swimming medals at the 2008 Paralympics in Beijing - Paralympics |publisher=Telegraph |date=2008-09-15 |accessdate=2010-05-02}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Brownhills]]\n* [[Pelsall]]\n* [[Walsall]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.walsall.gov.uk/index/aldridge_in_history.htm Walsall council local history]\n* [http://www.walsall.gov.uk/localhistorycentre/Local_Towns/aldridge.asp Even more local history]\n* {{Genuki|county=STS|Aldridge}}\n* {{OpenDomesday|SK0600|aldridge|Aldridge}}\n\n{{West Midlands County}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in the West Midlands (county)]]\n[[Category:Walsall]]\n[[Category:Aldridge|*]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|other uses of the term Aldridge|Aldridge (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country = England\n|map_type= West Midlands\n|coordinates = {{coord|52.606|-1.91787|display=inline,title}}\n|static_image_name= St Mary's Church, Aldridge - 03.JPG\n|static_image_caption= St Mary's Church, Aldridge\n|population = 39,348\n|population_ref = ([[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census.Ward]])<ref name=\"key\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/reports/localarea?compare=E05001308|title=Brownhills Ward (as of 2011)|publisher=Office for National Statistics|accessdate=26 June 2019}}</ref>\n|official_name= Aldridge\n|metropolitan_borough= [[Metropolitan Borough of Walsall|Walsall]]\n|region= West Midlands\n|metropolitan_county= [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]]\n|constituency_westminster= [[Aldridge-Brownhills (UK Parliament constituency)|Aldridge-Brownhills]]\n|london_distance= {{convert|128|mi|km|abbr=on}} [[Boxing the compass|SE]]\n|post_town= WALSALL\n|postcode_district = WS9\n|postcode_area= WS\n|dial_code= 01543, 01922\n|os_grid_reference= SK056009\n}}\n\n[[File:Gold postbox on the High Street - geograph.org.uk - 3132414.jpg|thumb|Gold postbox on the High Street]]\n\n'''Aldridge''' is a town and civil parish in the [[Walsall Metropolitan Borough|Walsall Borough]], [[West Midlands (region)|West Midlands]], [[England]]. [[Historic counties of England|Historically]] a village that was part of [[Staffordshire]] until 1974.\n\nIt is {{convert|3|mi}} from [[Brownhills]], {{convert|5|mi|0}} north east of [[Walsall]], {{convert|6|mi}} from [[Sutton Coldfield]] and {{convert|7|mi}} from [[Lichfield]]. Aldridge has a mixture of social and private housing, there is a large 1960s built shopping centre which has fairly high occupation rates, and a large number of industrial estates supporting both heavy and light industries.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Aldridge war memorial - 02.JPG|thumb|Aldridge war memorial]]\n\nAldridge was recorded as a settlement in the [[Domesday Book]] of 1086, though the now much larger settlement of Walsall was not.<ref>[http://www.haughton.net/domesdaybookplaces_a.htm THE DOMESDAY BOOK INDEX 1086 - 'A' Places ( Domesday Book Settlements / Places )<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928030248/http://www.haughton.net/domesdaybookplaces_a.htm |date=28 September 2007 }}</ref> It was valued at 15 shillings under the name of \"Alrewic\", which may have originated from an abundance of Alder trees in the area.<ref>[http://www.walsall.gov.uk/aldridge_in_history.htm Aldridge in history<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Another suggestion is that the name \"Aldbridge\" means \"outlying farm among alder-trees\", from the [[Old English]] ''alor'' and ''w\u012bc''.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Place-names of Great Britain and Ireland|last=Field|first=John|date=1980|publisher=David & Charles|isbn=0389201545|location=Newton Abbot, Devon|oclc=6964610|page=23}}</ref>\n\nAldridge began as a small agricultural settlement, with farming being the most common occupation up until the 19th century.\n\nIn the 1800s, Aldridge became an industrial town with [[coal mine]]s and [[lime kiln]]s. The coal and clay in the area prompted many to set up collieries and brickworks. Aldridge clay is especially useful in the manufacture of blue bricks. The 1881 census shows that the mines and brickworks were major employers. Because the coal and clay beneath the eastern side of Aldridge (towards Stonnall) is located much deeper under the surface, extraction of this coal and clay would not have been economically viable. As a result, farms continued to dominate the eastern part, though a sand quarry was set up and still remains on Birch Lane.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070621175821/http://www.btinternet.com/~aldridgelhs/HISTORY.htm A Brief History<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nDuring the 20th century, modern shops were built in the centre of Aldridge, as well as council buildings. After the [[Second World War]] Aldridge became a [[dormitory town]], or [[suburb]], of [[Birmingham]]. A small airport called Aldridge Airport was used during the Second World War and after was used for passenger services.\n\nAldridge became an [[Urban district (Great Britain and Ireland)|urban district]] in [[Staffordshire]] in 1894. Other [[village]]s within the district included [[Pelsall]], [[Walsall Wood]], [[Clayhanger, Walsall|Clayhanger]] and [[Streetly]]. This merged with [[Brownhills]] in 1966 to form [[Aldridge-Brownhills Urban District|Aldridge-Brownhills]], and then became part of the Metropolitan Borough of Walsall in 1974.\n\n==Demography==\nThe recorded population in 2011 in 26,988.<ref>[http://www.statistics.gov.uk/census2001/west_midlands_urban_area.asp National Statistics Online - Census 2001<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n== Politics ==\nSince 1979, Aldridge's [[Member of Parliament|MP]] was [[Richard Shepherd]] ([[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]), the MP for [[Aldridge-Brownhills (UK Parliament constituency)|Aldridge-Brownhills]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.election.demon.co.uk/1997EB.html |title=British Parliamentary Election results 1997-: English Boroughs part 1 |publisher=Election.demon.co.uk |date=1995-03-01 |accessdate=2010-05-02| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100503052817/http://www.election.demon.co.uk/1997EB.html| archivedate= 3 May 2010 <!--DASHBot-->|url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.election.demon.co.uk/1983EB.html |title=United Kingdom Parliamentary Election results 1983-97: English Boroughs part 1 |publisher=Election.demon.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2010-05-02}}</ref> He stood down at the 2015 General Election. In May 2015 [[Wendy Morton]] was selected as the new MP. Aldridge-Brownhills is a safe Conservative seat.\n\nAldridge is made up of two council wards: Aldridge Central & South, Aldridge North & Walsall Wood. There are three Conservative Councillors for Aldridge Central & South: John Murray, John Rochelle & Tim Wilson.\nAldridge North & Walsall Wood is also covered by three Conservative councillors: Keith Sears, Anthony Harris and Gary Clarke.<ref>[http://www.walsall.gov.uk/index/council_and_democracy/decision_making_in_walsall/councillors.htm#acs Current Walsall Councillors]</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nAldridge has a number of primary and secondary schools. The primary schools are Cooper and Jordan (CE), Leighswood, St Mary of the Angels (Catholic) and Whetstone Field (Redhouse primary school was closed in the summer of 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.walsall.gov.uk/CMISWebPublic/Binary.ashx?Document=1118 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-07-30 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723053233/http://www2.walsall.gov.uk/CMISWebPublic/Binary.ashx?Document=1118 |archivedate=2011-07-23 }}</ref>). The secondary schools are [[Aldridge School]] and [[St Francis of Assisi Catholic Technology College]].\n\n==Industry and commerce==\nIn Aldridge there are a number of factories, mostly located on Empire Industrial Park, but also towards Walsall Wood along the main road, Northgate. Some of the most notable factories include the large [[Ibstock]] brick works,  and the [[GKN Driveline|GKN Driveshafts]] factory, although the latter company closed in recent years due to relocation and cheaper foreign imports. [[Birlec]], a manufacturer of industrial furnaces relocated to Aldridge in the late 1950s, but has since closed. Aldridge Plastics Ltd, a plastics injection moulder, was set up in the town in 1968 and continued trading for almost 40 years before ceasing production in 2007. From January 2011, GFP Engineering Ltd, a Glass Reinforced Plastic (GRP) moulding company, will commence trading after relocating from nearby Lichfield.{{citation needed|reason=update evidence required|date=November 2014}} There is also a marina, Aldridge Marina, which recently underwent full refurbishment offering facilities for canal boat moorers.\n\nMost of the towns shops are located either on High Street, Anchor Road, or in the shopping area known as \"The Parade\". Well-known shops here include [[WH Smith]], [[Iceland]] supermarket, [[Home Bargains]], and [[Boots The Chemist]]. A purpose-built [[Safeway (UK)]] opened in 1992 and started operating as a [[Morrisons]] from 2004. [[B & M]] took over the former [[Focus DIY]] in Coppice Lane and opened its doors for the first time on 1 August 2015. One of the oldest traders in Aldridge is R.H.N. Riley Insurances on Anchor Rd, they have been trading since 1957 and in Aldridge since about 1970. Also in the area is the relatively newly opened Wetherspoons Public House - it has refurbished the former Avion cinema, latterly a bingo hall before the transition to pub. Many of the original features have been retained including the protected facade. There are a good deal of eateries in the town and these are regularly enjoyed by locals and travellers from further afield.\n\n== Transport ==\n\nAldridge is served by local bus services. Many of the buses in Aldridge were renumbered in April 2010 as part of National Express West Midlands' attempt to simplify bus services in and around the Walsall area. Bus operators operating services through Aldridge are\n[[Diamond West Midlands]] and [[National Express West Midlands]]. Services operated are to Walsall, Birmingham, Brownhills and Lichfield.\n\n[[File:Aldridge station, with Society Special train, 1951 (geograph 5039140).jpg|thumb|Aldridge station, with Society Special train, 1951]]\n\n[[Aldridge railway station]] was on the [[Sutton Park Line]] running from Walsall to [[Birmingham]] via Sutton Coldfield. It also had a direct link to [[Wolverhampton]] on the now defunct [[Wolverhampton and Walsall Railway]]. As well as a direct link to Brownhills via Walsall Wood although this closed in 1960s. The station had services to Walsall, Birmingham, Wolverhampton and Brownhills that operated services for passengers. The station was closed in 1966 and since then the line has been used only for freight. Ongoing speculation about returning passenger services to Aldridge, which would require a new station to be built, has continued with the apparent inclusion of Aldridge and [[Streetly]] stations on a map in the 2016 West Midlands Strategic Transport Plan.<ref>https://www.wmca.org.uk/media/1371/2016-06-01-mfg-summary-document_wmca.pdf</ref>\n\n== Sports, recreation and entertainment ==\nAldridge has a cricket and hockey club called \"The Stick and Wicket\", located on the green behind the parish church, [[St. Mary's Church, Aldridge|St. Mary's]], and the Masonic Hall. Aldridge Hockey Club merged with Walsall Hockey Club in 2011; it is now known as Aldridge & Walsall Hockey Club.<ref>http://www.awhockey.co.uk</ref>\n\nAldridge Sailing Club was formed in 1967 and celebrated its 50th anniversary in 2017. \nIt is an RYA affiliated club and offers regular training courses. It is located on Barns lane / Stubbers Green Road. www.aldridgesc.org.uk\n\nAldridge Rugby Football Club was formed in 1998 from an amalgamation of two established rugby clubs based in Birmingham: Witton and Old Centrals.\nThe club is based on the former Old Centrals sports ground at Bourne Vale in Aldridge and currently plays in Midlands 5 West (North), fielding three senior sides.\n\nAldridge Compass Suites (based at the Masonic Hall on the Green) is a venue for wedding receptions, christenings and other functions.\n\nThe Aldridge Youth Theatre, was officially opened by the actor [[Bernard Hepton]] and is located on Noddy Park Road by the Croft. It is run by a group of volunteers and puts on a variety of plays throughout the year. A pantomime is usually staged in January.\n\nAir Cadets: 425 (Aldridge) Squadron, part of Staffordshire Wing of the [[Air Training Corps]] was formed in 1941 and currently occupies a purpose-built HQ close to the village centre. The Squadron is run by uniformed [[RAFVR(T)]] officers and ATC SNCO adult staff, assisted by civilian instructors and a padre.\n\nThe 36th Walsall 1st Aldridge scout group is located on Middlemore Lane, opposite Anchor Meadow, and runs Beaver, Cub, Scout and Explorer sections for boys aged 6 and upwards. The beavers are aged 6\u20138, cubs are aged 8\u201310/11, scouts are aged 11\u201314 and explorers are aged 14\u201318.\n\nThe Methodist church, is used by 1st Aldridge Girl guides, as well as two brownie groups and a rainbow group. The rainbows group is for girls aged 5\u20137, the brownies for girls aged 7\u201310, and guides aged 10\u201314. Older girls do take part, and are known as the senior section.\n\nSt. Mary's Parish Church has one of the largest church youth groups in the area.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}} Around 90 young people, between the ages of 13 and 18, attend the group. The group also hosts an annual summer camp in Wales (in recent years attracting over 100 teenagers), as well as a weekend away in February.\n\nThe 33rd Walsall Scout group is based at Aldridge Methodist Church and holds Beavers, Cubs and scouts for boys and girls aged 6\u201314. They go on annual scout camps and have been to Beaudesert Campsite and Blackwell Adventure.\n\nThe 49th Walsall Scout Group is the third Scout Group in Aldridge based at St. Thomas's Church at the bottom of St Thomas Close, on the estate just off Lazy Hill Road and Greenwood Road, it also caters for boys and girls between the ages of 6 and 18.\n\n==Suburbs==\nSuburbs and villages of the town include: Castlefort (Part), [[Walsall Wood]] (Part), Leighswood, Druids Heath.\n\n===Military===\n[[Air Chief Marshal]] Sir [[Stuart Peach|Stuart William Peach]], [[Order of the British Empire|GBE]], [[Order of the Bath|KCB]], [[Aide-de-camp|ADC]], [[Deputy Lieutenant|DL]] was educated at Aldridge Grammar School.<ref>[https://www.gov.uk/government/people/stuart-peach]</ref>\n\n=== Military honours ===\n[[Charles George Bonner]] VC, DSC (29 December 1884 \u2013 7 February 1951), born in Aldridge, was an English recipient of the [[Victoria Cross]], the highest and most prestigious award for gallantry in the face of the enemy that can be awarded to [[United Kingdom|British]] and [[Commonwealth#Great Britain|Commonwealth]] forces. Bonner Grove is a well-maintained neighbourhood of social housing flats and privately owned houses in Aldridge that remembers his name.\n\n=== Sports men and women ===\n[[Charles Holland (cyclist)|Charles Holland]] was a road bicycle racer, and one of the first two Britons to ride the Tour de France. Rode in Olympic Games: Los Angeles 1932 and Berlin 1936.{{Citation needed|date=February 2011}}\n\n[[Vic Milne]] had a doctor's surgery in Portland Road,  Aldridge.{{citation needed|date=March 2013}}  Played football for [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]], including an appearance in the [[1924 FA Cup Final]] where his team were defeated 2-0 by [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]].\n\n[[Lee Sinnott]] (born 12 July 1965 in Aldridge) is an English ex-professional footballer and was the manager of [[Farsley Celtic F.C.|Farsley Celtic]], whom he led to promotion three times in four years. He went on to manage [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] for a short period. He began his career at [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]] as an apprentice, and played in the 1984 [[FA Cup]] final for his next club [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] in 1984. He captained [[Huddersfield Town F.C.|Huddersfield Town]] to [[Football League Second Division|Division Two]] playoff glory in 1995.\n\n[[Colin Charvis]], former captain of the [[Wales national rugby union team]], went to the Redhouse School in Aldridge.<ref>http://www.birminghammail.net/news/top-stories/2010/05/15/former-wales-rugby-captain-colin-charvis-returned-to-his-walsall-roots-97319-26448153/</ref>\n\nSwimmer [[Ellie Simmonds]] won two gold medals at both the 2008 and 2012 [[Paralympics]]. She attended Cooper and Jordan Primary School, then [[Aldridge School]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Davies |first=Gareth A |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/paralympicsport/2964791/Eleanor-Simmonds-claims-two-gold-swimming-medals-at-the-2008-Paralympics-in-Beijing-Paralympics.html |title=Eleanor Simmonds claims two gold swimming medals at the 2008 Paralympics in Beijing - Paralympics |publisher=Telegraph |date=2008-09-15 |accessdate=2010-05-02}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Brownhills]]\n* [[Pelsall]]\n* [[Walsall]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.walsall.gov.uk/index/aldridge_in_history.htm Walsall council local history]\n* [http://www.walsall.gov.uk/localhistorycentre/Local_Towns/aldridge.asp Even more local history]\n* {{Genuki|county=STS|Aldridge}}\n* {{OpenDomesday|SK0600|aldridge|Aldridge}}\n\n{{West Midlands County}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in the West Midlands (county)]]\n[[Category:Walsall]]\n[[Category:Aldridge|*]]\n", "name_user": "Charlesdrakew", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSuburbs:add heading", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aldridge"}
{"title_page": "John Prine", "text_new": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American country singer/songwriter}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = John Prine\n| image = John Prine by Ron Baker.jpg\n| image_size =\n| caption = Prine at MerleFest, Wilkesboro N.C. (2006)\n| landscape = yes\n| background = solo_singer\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1946|10|10}}\n| death_date =\n| birth_place = [[Maywood, Illinois]], U.S.\n| instrument = {{unbulleted list|[[Vocals]]|[[Guitar]]}}\n| genre = [[Country folk]], [[Bluegrass music|bluegrass]], [[Americana (music)|Americana]]\n| occupation ={{hlist|[[Singer-songwriter]]|[[guitarist]]}}\n| years_active = 1971\u2013present\n| label = {{hlist|[[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]|[[Asylum Records|Asylum]]|[[Oh Boy Records|Oh Boy]]|[[Rhino Records|Rhino]]}}\n| associated_acts = {{unbulletedlist|[[Steve Goodman]]|[[Iris DeMent]]}} <!--and many other artists too numerous to list here-->\n| website = {{URL|johnprine.net|JohnPrine.net}}\n}}\n'''John Prine''' (born October 10, 1946) is an [[Americans|American]] [[country folk]] [[singer-songwriter]]. He has been active as a composer, recording artist, and live performer since the early 1970s, and is known for an often humorous style of country music that has elements of [[protest music|protest]] and social commentary.\n\nBorn and raised in [[Maywood, Illinois]], Prine learned to play the guitar at the age of 14. He attended classes at Chicago's [[Old Town School of Folk Music]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/oldtownschool/status/989572224213450752 |title=John Prine OTSFM Registration Card |publisher=Old Town School of Folk Music |date=1964-09-17 |accessdate=2018-04-26}}</ref> After serving in [[West Germany]] with the U.S. armed forces, he moved to [[Chicago]] in the late 1960s, where he worked as a mailman, writing and singing songs as a hobby.\n\nA member of Chicago's [[folk revival]], he was discovered by [[Kris Kristofferson]], resulting in the production of Prine's [[John Prine (album)|self-titled debut album]] with [[Atlantic Records]] in 1971. After receiving critical acclaim, Prine focused on his musical career, recording three more albums for Atlantic. He then signed to [[Asylum Records]], where he recorded an additional three albums. In 1984 he co-founded [[Oh Boy Records]], an independent record label with which he would release most of his subsequent albums. After his battle with [[Squamous cell carcinoma|squamous cell cancer]] in 1998, Prine's vocals deepened into a gravelly voice.\n\nWidely cited as one of the most influential songwriters of his generation, Prine is known for humorous lyrics about love, life, and current events, as well as serious songs with social commentary, or which recollect melancholy tales from his life.\n\n==Early life==\nPrine is the son of William Prine. a [[Tool and die maker|tool-and-die]] maker, and Verna Hamm, a homemaker, both from [[Muhlenberg County, Kentucky|Muhlenberg County]], [[Kentucky]]. He grew up in the Maywood suburb of Chicago.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Barry|first=Dan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/10/arts/music/john-prine-endures-with-a-half-smile-and-a-song.html|title=John Prine Endures, With a Half-Smile and a Song|date=2016-04-06|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-30|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> He started playing guitar at age 14, taught by his brother, David.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shrout.co.uk/jpbackpage.html |title=John Prine Information |publisher=Shrout.co.uk |date=1946-10-10 |accessdate=2011-03-15}}</ref> He attended classes at Chicago's [[Old Town School of Folk Music]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/oldtownschool/status/98957222421345075 |title=John Prine OTSFM Registration Card |publisher=Old Town School of Folk Music |date=1964-09-17 |accessdate=2018-04-26}}</ref> Prine attended [[Proviso East High School]] in [[Maywood, Illinois]]. He was a mailman for five years and served in the [[United States Army|Army]] during the [[Vietnam War]] era, serving in Germany, before beginning his musical career in [[Chicago]].\n\nIn the late-1960s, while Prine was delivering mail, he began to sing at [[open mic]] evenings at the Fifth Peg on Armitage Avenue in Chicago. Prine was initially a spectator, reluctant to perform, but eventually did so in response to a \"You think you can do better?\" comment made to him by another performer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://devildick.blogspot.de/2012/02/john-prine-st-1971.html |title=The Devil's Music: John Prine \u2013 S/T \u2013 1971 |publisher=Devildick.blogspot.de |date=2012-02-07 |accessdate=2013-06-15}}</ref> ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' movie critic [[Roger Ebert]] heard him there and wrote the first review Prine ever received, calling him a great songwriter.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rogerebert.com/balder-and-dash/john-prine-american-legend |title=Roger Ebert's Journal: \"John Prine: American Legend\" |work=Chicago Sun-Times |accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref> He became a central figure in the Chicago [[American folk music revival|folk revival]], which also included such singer-songwriters as [[Steve Goodman]], [[Michael Peter Smith]], [[Bonnie Koloc]], [[Jim Post]], [[Tom Dundee]], [[Anne Hills]]  and [[Fred Holstein]]. Joined by such established musicians as [[Jethro Burns]] and [[Bob Gibson (musician)|Bob Gibson]], Prine performed frequently at a variety of Chicago clubs\u2014including the Earl of Old Town, the Quiet Knight, Dangling Conversation, Somebody Else's Troubles, The Fifth Peg, and the Bulls.\n\n==Career==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=October 2010}}\n\n=== 1970s ===\nIn 1971 Prine's [[John Prine (album)|self-titled debut album]] was released. He and friend Steve Goodman had each been active in the [[Chicago]] folk scene before being \"discovered\" by [[Kris Kristofferson]] (Kristofferson remarked that Prine wrote songs so good that \"we'll have to break his thumbs\").<ref name=\"Chilton, Martin 2013\">Chilton, Martin. \"John Prine: I Find the Human Condition Funny; John Prine, One of Bob Dylan's Favourite Songwriters, Is Appearing in the UK and Ireland. Here He Talks to Martin Chilton.\" Daily Telegraph [London, England] February 8, 2013, Web Edition Articles ed.: Print.</ref> The album included his signature songs \"Illegal Smile,\" \"[[Sam Stone (song)|Sam Stone]],\" and the folk and country standards \"[[Angel from Montgomery]]\" and \"[[Paradise (John Prine song)|Paradise]].\" The album also featured \"[[Hello In There]],\" a song about aging that was later covered by numerous artists, and \"Far From Me\", a lonely waltz about lost love for a waitress that Prine later said was his favorite of all his songs. The album received many positive reviews, and some hailed Prine as \"the next Dylan.\" [[Bob Dylan]] himself appeared unannounced at one of Prine's first [[New York City]] club appearances, anonymously backing him on harmonica.\n\nPrine's second album, ''[[Diamonds in the Rough (album)|Diamonds In The Rough]]'' (1972), was a surprise for many after the critical success of his first LP; it was an uncommercial, stripped-down affair that reflected Prine's fondness for bluegrass music and features songs reminiscent of [[Hank Williams]]. Highlights include the allegorical \"[[The Great Compromise (song)|The Great Compromise]],\" which includes a recitation and addresses the [[Vietnam War]], and the ballad \"Souvenirs,\" which Prine later recorded with Goodman.\n\nSubsequent albums include ''[[Sweet Revenge (John Prine album)|Sweet Revenge]]'' (1973), containing such fan favorites as \"Dear Abby,\" \"Grandpa Was a Carpenter,\" and \"Christmas in Prison,\" and [[Common Sense (John Prine album)|''Common Sense'']] (1975), with \"Come Back to Us Barbara Lewis Hare Krishna Beauregard\". The latter album was Prine's first to be charted in the US Top 100 by ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', reflecting growing commercial success. It was produced by Steve Cropper. Many veteran Prine fans view the release of 1978's ''[[Bruised Orange]]'' as a creative highpoint.{{Citation needed|date=October 2012}} The Steve Goodman-produced album gave listeners songs such as \"The Hobo Song,\" \"Sabu Visits the Twin Cities Alone,\" and the title track.\n\nIn 1974, singer [[David Allan Coe]] achieved considerable success on the country charts with \"[[You Never Even Called Me By My Name]]\", co-written by Prine and Goodman. The song good-naturedly spoofs stereotypical country music lyrics. Prine refused to take a songwriter's credit and the tune went to Goodman, although Goodman bought Prine a jukebox as a gift from his publishing royalties.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OMiLqHTvbKE|title=John Prine - You Never Even Call Me by My Name (1987)|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=October 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1975, Prine toured the U.S. and Canada with a full band featuring guitarist [[Arlen Roth]]. {{Asof|2014}}, this has been Prine's only tour with a full band.\n\nThe 1979 album ''[[Pink Cadillac (album)|Pink Cadillac]]'' features two songs produced by [[Sun Records]] founder [[Sam Phillips]], who by this time rarely did any studio work. The song \"Saigon,\" is about a Vietnam vet traumatized by the war (\"The static in my attic's gettin' ready to blow\"). During the recording, one of the guitar amps blew up (which is evident on the album). The other song Phillips produced is \"How Lucky,\" about Prine's hometown.\n\n=== 1980s ===\nIn 1981, rejecting the established model of the recording industry, which Prine felt exploited singers and songwriters, he co-founded the independent record label [[Oh Boy Records]]. His fans, supporting the project, sent him enough money to cover the costs, in advance, of his next album.<ref name=\":0\" /> Prine continued writing and recording albums throughout the 1980s  His songs continued to be covered by other artists; the country supergroup [[The Highwaymen (country supergroup)|The Highwaymen]] recorded \"The Twentieth Century Is Almost Over,\" which had been written by Prine and Goodman. Steve Goodman died of leukemia in 1984 and Prine continues to perform many of Goodman's songs in concert to this day, such as \"My Old Man.\"\n\n=== 1990s ===\nIn 1991, Prine released the [[Grammy Award]]-winning ''The Missing Years'', his first collaboration with producer and [[Tom Petty and the Heartbreakers|Heartbreakers]] bassist [[Howie Epstein]]. The title song records Prine's humorous take on what [[Jesus]] did in the unrecorded years between his childhood and [[Ministry of Jesus|ministry]]. In 1995, ''[[Lost Dogs and Mixed Blessings]]'' was released, another collaboration with Epstein. Prine followed in 1999 with ''[[In Spite of Ourselves]]'', which was unusual for him in that it contained only one original song; the rest were covers of classic country songs. All of the tracks are duets with well-known female country vocalists, including [[Lucinda Williams]], [[Emmylou Harris]], [[Connie Smith]], [[Patty Loveless]], [[Dolores Keane]], [[Trisha Yearwood]], and [[Iris DeMent]], notably on the title track.\n\n=== 2000s ===\nIn 2001, Prine co-starred in the [[Billy Bob Thornton]] movie ''[[Daddy & Them]]''. \"In Spite of Ourselves\" can be heard as the end credits roll.\n\nPrine recorded a version of [[Stephen Foster]]'s \"[[My Old Kentucky Home]]\" in 2004 for the compilation album ''[[Beautiful Dreamer (album)|Beautiful Dreamer]]'', which won the Grammy for Best Traditional Folk Album in 2004.\n\nIn 2005, Prine released his first all-new offering since ''Lost Dogs and Mixed Blessings'', the album ''[[Fair & Square]]'', which tended toward a more laid-back, acoustic approach. The album contains songs such as \"Safety Joe,\" about a man who has never taken any risks in his life, and also \"Some Humans Ain't Human,\" Prine's protest piece on the album, which talks about the ugly side of [[human nature]] and includes a quick shot at President [[George W. Bush]]. ''Fair & Square'' won the 2005 Grammy Award for Best Contemporary Folk Album. The album contains original songs plus two covers: [[A.P. Carter]]'s \"Bear Creek Blues\" and [[Blaze Foley]]'s \"Clay Pigeons.\"\n\n=== 2010s ===\nOn June 22, 2010, Oh Boy Records released a tribute album titled ''[[Broken Hearts and Dirty Windows: The Songs of John Prine]]''. The album features members of the modern folk revival including [[My Morning Jacket]], [[The Avett Brothers]], [[Conor Oberst and the Mystic Valley Band]], [[Old Crow Medicine Show]], [[Lambchop (band)|Lambchop]], [[Josh Ritter]], [[Drive-By Truckers]], [[Nickel Creek]]'s [[Sara Watkins]], [[Deer Tick (band)|Deer Tick]] featuring Liz Isenberg, [[Justin Townes Earle]], [[Those Darlins]], and [[Bon Iver]]'s [[Justin Vernon]].<ref name=\"broken hearts\">{{cite web|url=http://brokenheartsanddirtywindows.com/about.html |title=Broken Hearts and Dirty Windows: The Songs of John Prine; Oh Boy Records |publisher=brokenheartsanddirtywindows.com |accessdate=2012-02-18}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Prine was named winner of the PEN/Song Lyrics Award, given to two songwriters every other year by the [[PEN International|PEN]] New England chapter. The 2016 award was shared with [[Tom Waits]] and his songwriting collaborator wife [[Kathleen Brennan]]. Judges for the award included [[Peter Wolf]], [[Rosanne Cash]], [[Paul Simon]], [[Elvis Costello]] and others, as well as literary judge [[Salman Rushdie]].<ref>PEN+NE Song Lyric Award page http://www.pen-ne.org/lyrics/</ref> In 2016, Prine released ''[[For Better, or Worse]]'', a follow-up to ''[[In Spite of Ourselves]]'' from 1999. The album featured country music covers featuring some of the most prominent female voices in the genre including [[Alison Krauss]], [[Miranda Lambert]], [[Kacey Musgraves]] and [[Lee Ann Womack]] among others, as well as [[Iris DeMent]], the only artist to be featured on both albums.\n\nOn March 15, 2017 The American Currents exhibit opened at the Country Music Hall of Fame. The exhibit featured a pair of cowboy boots and jacket that he often wore on stage, his personal guitar and the original handwritten lyric to his hit, \"Angel From Montgomery.\" The American Currents Class of 2016 showcased artists who made a significant impact on country music in 2016, including [[Jason Aldean]], [[Kelsea Ballerini]], [[Ross Copperman]], [[The Earls of Leicester (band)|The Earls of Leicester]], [[Brett Eldredge]], [[Florida Georgia Line]], [[Mickey Guyton]], [[Natalie Hemby]], [[Sierra Hull]], [[Jason Isbell]], [[Miranda Lambert]], [[Jim Lauderdale]], [[Shane McAnally]], [[Lori McKenna]], [[William Michael Morgan]], [[Maren Morris]], [[Jon Pardi]], [[Dolly Parton]], [[Margo Price]], John Prine, [[RaeLynn]], [[Chris Stapleton|Chris and Morgane Stapleton]] and [[Randy Travis]]. Prine won his second Artist of the Year award at the 2017 [[Americana Music Honors & Awards]] after previously winning in 2005.\n\nOn February 8, 2018, Prine announced his first new album of original material in 13 years, titled ''[[The Tree of Forgiveness]]'', would be released on April 13. Produced by [[Dave Cobb]], the album was released on Prine's own Oh Boy Records and features guest artists [[Jason Isbell]], [[Amanda Shires]], [[Dan Auerbach]] and [[Brandi Carlile]]. Alongside the announcement, Prine released the track \"Summer's End\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/allsongs/2018/02/08/584219320/john-prine-to-release-his-first-album-of-new-songs-in-13-years |title=John Prine To Release His First Album Of New Songs In 13 Years |date=February 8, 2018 |work=NPR |first=Jacob |last=Ganz}}</ref> The album became Prine's highest-charting album on the ''Billboard'' 200.<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8366469/jason-aldean-scores-rearview-town-no-1-billboard-200 |title= Jason Aldean Scores Fourth No. 1 on Billboard 200 Albums Chart With 'Rearview Town'|date=April 22, 2018 |first= Keith|last= Caulfield |work=Billboard }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPrine is married to Fiona Whelan Prine, who is also his manager.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/e96aea5d3a1d9dd2c27ebeb88a61df28|title=John Prine in critical condition with COVID-19 symptoms|date=2020-03-29|website=AP NEWS|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nIn early 1998, Prine was diagnosed with [[Squamous cell carcinoma|squamous cell cancer]] on the right side of his neck. He had major surgery to remove a substantial amount of diseased tissue, followed by six weeks of [[radiation therapy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jpshrine.org/john_prine_letter.html |title=John Prine personal letter to his fans about his cancer |publisher=Jpshrine.org |accessdate=2011-03-15}}</ref> The surgery removed a piece of his neck and severed a few nerves in his tongue, while the radiation damaged some salivary glands. A year of recuperation and speech therapy was necessary before he could perform again.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/10/arts/music/john-prine-endures-with-a-half-smile-and-a-song.html | title=John Prine Endures, With a Half-Smile and a Song | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | date=April 6, 2016}}</ref> The operation altered his vocals, and has added a gravelly tone to his voice.<ref>[http://home.mchsi.com/~rburhead/2005/05concertreviews_IL.htm John Prine concert reviews] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110526024957/http://home.mchsi.com/~rburhead/2005/05concertreviews_IL.htm |date=May 26, 2011 }} June 4, 2005</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Prine learned he had cancer in his left lung and underwent surgery to remove it. After the surgery, a physical therapist put him through an unusual workout to build stamina: Prine was required to run up and down his house stairs, grab his guitar while still out of breath and sing two songs. Six months later, he was touring again.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nFiona Whelan Prine revealed on March 19, 2020 that she had tested positive for the [[COVID-19]] [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|virus]] and had been quarantined in her home apart from Prine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/music/news/john-prine-in-critical-condition-after-hospitalization-for-coronavirus/ar-BB11SC6n|title=John Prine in Critical Condition After Hospitalization for Coronavirus\n|work=[[MSN]]|access-date=March 29, 2020 |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref>On March 29, 2020, Prine's family announced that he had been hospitalized on March 26 after suddenly experiencing symptoms associated with COVID-19. He was [[intubated]] on the evening of March 28, and was in critical condition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/john-prine-covid-19-symptoms-974909/ |title=John Prine Hospitalized with COVID-19 Symptoms: 'His Situation Is Critical'|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=March 29, 2020 |date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> On March 30, Whelan Prine tweeted that she had recovered and that her husband was now in stable condition, though she cautioned that this does not mean he is improving.<ref>{{cite web |title=Singer John Prine is in stable condition, his wife says |url=https://apnews.com/9590a8f408545383d221b20cde37816c |website=AP NEWS |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=en |date=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/music/story/2020-03-30/john-prine-coronavirus-stable|title=John Prine, still hospitalized with COVID-19, is now stable, his wife says|last=D'Zurilla|first=Christie|date=March 30, 2020|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>On April 3, 2020, Whelan Prine gave another update on her husband's condition saying that he was currently in his eighth day in [[ICU]] and that he is still on a ventilator and needs quite a bit of help with his breathing. He has [[pneumonia]] in both lungs and he has also developed some peripheral issues that are being treated with medications including antibiotics. She said that her husband is still very ill but she remains hopeful that he can continue to fight this and come home where his family can care for him.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/john-prine-covid-19-update-977746/?fbclid=IwAR0o9yz_1MEK55qfwuzJi-xtXGyplm9PLzmuOGlnOsTaUYNjghOkl6lSFkg|title=John Prine\u2019s Wife Fiona: \u2018He Is Very Ill and Yet I Remain Hopeful\u2019|last=Doyle|first=Patrick|date=April 3, 2020|publisher=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Influence==\nPrine is widely regarded as one of the most influential songwriters of his generation.\n\nIn 2009, [[Bob Dylan]] told ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' that Prine was one of his favorite writers, stating \"Prine's stuff is pure [[Marcel Proust|Proustian]] [[existentialism]]. Midwestern mindtrips to the nth degree. And he writes beautiful songs. I remember when [[Kris Kristofferson]] first brought him on the scene. 'Sam Stone' featuring the wonderfully evocative line: 'There\u2019s a hole in daddy's arm where all the money goes, and Jesus Christ died for nothing I suppose.'<ref>\"Prine, John\", ''Encyclopedia of Popular Music'', 4th ed. Ed. Colin Larkin. Oxford Music Online. Oxford University Press. Web. September 27, 2014</ref> All that stuff about \"Sam Stone,\" the soldier junkie daddy, and \"Donald and Lydia\", where people make love from ten miles away. Nobody but Prine could write like that.\"<ref name=\"huff_post_dylan\">{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/04/15/bob-dylan-exclusive-inter_n_187216.html|title=Bob Dylan Exclusive Interview: Reveals His Favorite Songwriters, Thoughts On His Own Cult Figure Status|last=Flanagan|first=Bill |date=April 15, 2009|work=Huffington Post|accessdate=2009-07-12}}</ref>\n\n[[Johnny Cash]], in his autobiography ''Cash'', wrote, \"I don't listen to music much at the farm, unless I'm going into songwriting mode and looking for inspiration. Then I'll put on something by the writers I've admired and used for years--[[Rodney Crowell]], John Prine, [[Guy Clark]], and the late [[Steve Goodman]] are my Big Four...\"<ref name=\"cash_prine\">{{cite book|last=Cash|first=Johnny |author2=Carr|others=Patrick |title=Cash|publisher=[[HarperCollins]]|year=2003|page=189}}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Waters]], when asked by ''[[Word Magazine]]'' in 2008 if he heard [[Pink Floyd]]'s influence in newer British bands like [[Radiohead]], replied, \"I don't really listen to Radiohead. I listened to the albums and they just didn't move me in the way, say, John Prine does. His is just extraordinarily eloquent music\u2014and he lives on that plane with [[Neil Young]] and Lennon.\"<ref name=\"word_waters\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wordmagazine.co.uk/content/word-exclusive-roger-waters|title=Word Interview Exclusive: Roger Waters|work=Word Magazine|date=April 13, 2008|accessdate=2009-07-12|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081024104158/http://www.wordmagazine.co.uk/content/word-exclusive-roger-waters|archivedate=October 24, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\n\n===Grammy Awards===\nThe [[Grammy Awards]] are annually presented by [[The Recording Academy]] for outstanding achievements and artistic excellence in the recording arts. Prine has won two Grammy Awards out of eleven nominations.<ref name=Grammy /> \n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:85%;\"\n|-\n! width=\"5\"|Year\n! width=\"350\"| Nominated work\n! width=\"350\"| Category\n! width=\"65\"| Result\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1972\n| John Prine\n| [[Grammy Award for Best New Artist|Best New Artist]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1986\n| ''[[German Afternoons]]''\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Contemporary Folk Album|Best Contemporary Folk Recording]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1988\n| ''[[John Prine Live]]''\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Contemporary Folk Album|Best Contemporary Folk Recording]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1991\n| ''[[The Missing Years (album)|The Missing Years]]''\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Contemporary Folk Album|Best Contemporary Folk Album]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1995\n| ''[[Lost Dogs and Mixed Blessings]]''\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Contemporary Folk Album|Best Contemporary Folk Album]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1997\n| ''[[Live on Tour]]''\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Contemporary Folk Album|Best Contemporary Folk Album]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1999\n| ''[[In Spite of Ourselves]]''\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Contemporary Folk Album|Best Contemporary Folk Album]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2005\n| ''[[Fair & Square]]''\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Contemporary Folk Album|Best Contemporary Folk Album]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"3\"|2018\n| ''[[The Tree of Forgiveness]]''\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Americana Album|Best Americana Album]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| \"Summer's End\" \n| [[Grammy Award for Best American Roots Song|Best Americana Roots Song]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| \"Knockin' On Your Screen Door\"\n| [[Grammy Award for Best American Roots Song|Best Americana Roots Song]]\n| {{nom}}\n|}<ref name=Grammy>{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/john-prine|title=John Prine|publisher=[[The Recording Academy]]|website=grammy.com}}</ref>\n\n===Other Accolades===\n*During 2005 at the request of [[United States Poet Laureate|U.S. Poet Laureate]] [[Ted Kooser]], John Prine became the first singer/songwriter to read and perform at the [[Library of Congress]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/today/cyberlc/feature_wdesc.php?rec=3677|title=A Literary Evening with John Prine and Ted Kooser|publisher=[[Library of Congress]]|date=March 9, 2005|access-date=2018-05-22}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\" \n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n! colspan=\"6\"| Peak chart positions\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Label\n|- style=\"font-size: smaller\"\n! style=\"width:45px;\"| [[Billboard 200|US]]<br><ref name=billboard200>{{cite web |url=https://